tables_with_autovacuum_off.sql:
SELECT relname, reloptions
FROM pg_class
WHERE 'autovacuum_enabled=false' = ANY(reloptions);

host_disk_space.detail:
Shows how full the most-utilised filesystem on the host is (from pgSCV / Yandex Cloud metrics).
If the data volume runs out of space, PostgreSQL can no longer write — the cluster stops abruptly and data can be corrupted. That is why ≥90% is treated as critical for any role, primary and replica alike: the overall Health Score is forced into the red zone.
What to do:
• free up space — old WAL and logs, temporary files, stale backups;
• grow the volume;
• check table and index bloat;
• make sure WAL is not accumulating because of inactive replication slots.
